<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-01-23T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-01-23T11:00:00-05:00" n="140" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d140">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/1–2345: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                            to the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi></persName>)</head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-01-23T12:00:00-04:00">January 23,
                                1945—noon</date>.</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>117. The President has let me read your exceedingly interesting telegram of
                        January 14, No. 141500 NCR 6810,<note n="40" xml:id="d140fn40">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_172">p. 172</ref>.</note>
                        and I want you to know how much we appreciate the constructive work that you
                        are doing. Appropriate steps have been taken to explore the difficulties you
                        have had with our own military subordinates.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>